Social Media Do’s and Don’ts for College Students

Do’s

Keep your LinkedIn and GitHub profiles updated from the beginning
It’s easy to think you’ll complete them later when you have achievements to show, but an incomplete profile doesn’t create a
good impression. Even basic details like your course, college, year, and what you’re learning right now are enough to start 
with.

Think before posting anything
Before sharing something online, just ask yourself if you’d be comfortable with a professor or recruiter seeing it. If there’s
even a small doubt, it’s better not to post. Once something is online, it’s not easy to remove it completely.

Use a password manager
Using the same password everywhere is risky. Tools like Google Password Manager or Bitwarden make it easier to manage strong 
passwords and keep your accounts safe with minimal effort.

Turn on two-factor authentication (2FA)
For important accounts like email, LinkedIn, GitHub, or even Instagram, enabling 2FA adds an extra layer of security. Even if 
someone gets your password, they won’t be able to access your account without your phone.

Check information before sharing
If something looks too shocking or unrealistic, it’s better to verify it first. Sharing incorrect information can harm your 
credibility, especially on professional platforms.

Review your privacy settings regularly
Social media platforms often update their settings. Something that was private before might not be anymore, so it’s a good 
idea to check your settings every few months.

Log out from shared devices
Whenever you use a public or shared computer, make sure you log out of your accounts. It’s a small step that can prevent major 
problems.

Don’ts

Avoid sharing personal details online
Information like your phone number, address, Aadhaar, PAN, or ID cards should never be shared publicly. Even small details can 
be misused.

Don’t post academic content related to exams or assignments
Sharing question papers, answers, or internal work online can lead to serious consequences and goes against academic integrity.

Stay away from online arguments
Getting into arguments in comments or messages rarely leads to anything positive. It’s better to ignore and move on.

Don’t click on suspicious links
Links sent by unknown people, even if they look real, can be harmful. If something feels off, it’s safer not to open it.

Avoid sharing your live location
Posting your location while you’re still there, especially if you’re alone or at odd hours, can be unsafe. It’s better to share
it later.
